:"1160.","1170":"1170","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, Engleska, United Kingdom","Ardevora, Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"1160–1230":"1160–1230","1162–Male":"1162–Zesnulý","1170–1245":"1170–1245","1185–1255":"1185–1255","1130–1200":"1130–1200","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","1255":"1255","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1130":"1130","1162":"1162","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, Anglie, United Kingdom","Ardevora, Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1160–1230":"1160–1230","1162–Male":"1162–Afdød","1170–1245":"1170–1245","1185–1255":"1185–1255","1130–1200":"1130–1200","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","1255":"1255","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1130":"1130","1162":"1162","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Ardevora, Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1160–1230":"1160–1230","1162–Male":"1162–Overleden","1170–1245":"1170–1245","1185–1255":"1185–1255","1130–1200":"1130–1200","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","1255":"1255","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1130":"1130","1162":"1162","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ardevora, Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1160–1230":"1160–1230","1162–Male":"1162–Deceased","1170–1245":"1170–1245","1185–1255":"1185–1255","1130–1200":"1130–1200","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","1255":"1255","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1130":"1130","1162":"1162","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Ardevora, Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Petit","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Alain, Michel, Normand, Mireille, Philippe, Pierre, Achille, Armand, Jean Claude, Jean Jacques, Ketly, Adrien.","French, Walloon, Catalan, English, Jewish (from southern France), West Indian (mainly Haiti), and Mauritian: from (Old) French, Catalan, and Middle English <i>petit</i> ‘small’, hence a nickname for a small man (or an ironic nickname for a big man), or a distinguishing name for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name. Compare   Little  ,   Petee  , and   Petite  .","History: Charles Petit from Anneville-Ambourville in Seine-Maritime, France, married Jeanne Rossignol (Martin and Renée Desjardins) in Quebec City, QC, in 1670. Nicolas Petit <i>dit</i> Lapré/Laprée from Le Gué-d'Alleré in Charente-Maritime, France, married Marie Pouponnel in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1656. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Gobin from Lyon in Rhône married Marguerite Véron in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1692. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Saint-Pierre from Évreux in Eure, France, married Judith Miville in Quebec City, QC, in 1758; see also   St. Pierre  . — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."],"variants":[{"name":"Pattee","meanings":["Altered form of French (Nord) <b>Pety</b>: variant of   Petit  . This surname was brought to North America from England."]},{"name":"Petion","meanings":["French and Haitian (<b>Pétion</b>): diminutive of   Petit  . This surname was brought to the US from Haiti, where it is by far most common."]},{"name":"Petite","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Celestine, Jacques.","French: from the feminine form of   Petit   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Petitt","meanings":["English: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettett","meanings":["English: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Little","meanings":["English: nickname for a small man (if not ironic), or distinguishing epithet for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, from Middle English <i>littel</i>, Old English <i>lȳtel</i> (see   Light   3).","Irish: translation into English of Gaelic <b>Ó Beagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Beagán</i>’ (see   Began  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of any of various European surnames meaning ‘little’, e.g. French   Petit  , Polish <b>Mały</b> (see   Maly   1)."]},{"name":"Petee","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettit","meanings":["English (mainly southeastern): variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Petito","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Carmine, Pasquale, Antonio, Rocco, Alfonzo, Alphonso, Antimo, Emilio, Giovanni, Giuseppe, Orazio, Salvatore, Silvio, Tullio, Virginio.","Italian: nickname for a small man (or an ironic nickname for a tall one), from dialect <i>petito</i> ‘small’ or from the personal name <i>Petito</i>; compare French   Petit  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Kyong, Kyong Suk, Young, Chae, Chi Young, Hang, Kil, Rin, Sang Hun, Chang, Chong, Insoo, Kum, Sun Young, Yom, Young Hwan.  Cambodian Kiwan, Oeurn, Phoeun, Pich, Saroeuth, Seung, Sophath, Sophea, Yoeun, Phan, Son.  Indian Shanti, Harendra.","Indian (Uttar Pradesh): Brahmin name, from Sanskrit <i>om</i>, the Hindu sacred and mystic syllable uttered at the beginning of prayers.","Cambodian: written ឱម, corresponding to the exclamation of solemn affirmation, of Sanskrit origin (see 1 above), chanted by Buddhist monks."],"variants":[{"name":"Oum","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Heang, Hye, Kam, Kan, Kheng, Khin, Kun, Sang, Sok, Phong, Yom, Yoo, Youn, Cuong, Phal, Samnang, Tin.  Cambodian Sokha, Chheang, Choeun, Moeun, Roeun, Sambath, Samoeun, Savuth, Soeun, Sopheap.","Cambodian: written អ៊ុំ, from a Khmer word denoting an elder sibling of one's parent (i.e. ‘uncle’ or ‘aunt’). Compare   Om   3 and   Um   2."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir John Petit of Ardevora was born in 1160, in Philleigh, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom as the son of Otes Petit Lord of Ardevora. He had at least 1 son with Muriel Whalesborough. He died in 1230, in his hometown, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1160–1230":"1160–1230","1162–Male":"1162–Surnud","1170–1245":"1170–1245","1185–1255":"1185–1255","1130–1200":"1130–1200","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","1255":"1255","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1130":"1130","1162":"1162","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ardevora, Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1160–1230":"1160–1230","1162–Male":"1162–Kuollut","1170–1245":"1170–1245","1185–1255":"1185–1255","1130–1200":"1130–1200","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","1255":"1255","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1130":"1130","1162":"1162","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ardevora, Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":